Why SIMA?

As AI systems accumulate long-term memory, the total memory corpus can grow far beyond the model's active context window.

A naive architecture might conceptually operate like:

Prompt
  |
  v
Search large memory corpus
  |
  v
Retrieve large memory objects
  |
  v
Inject into context

This can create several problems:

Increasing retrieval cost
Increasing context consumption
Retrieval of irrelevant information
Context pollution
Redundant memories
Difficulty scaling to very large memory stores
Increased latency

SIMA proposes a progressive retrieval architecture:

Prompt
  |
  v
Identify likely category
  |
  v
Search compact memory representations
  |
  v
Rank candidates
  |
  v
Expand only relevant memories
  |
  v
Assemble final context

The architecture does not claim to increase the model's physical context window.

Instead, it aims to increase the effective usable memory capacity by reducing how much irrelevant information must be loaded into the active context.

Core Principle

SIMA separates the representation used to store a memory from the representation used to find that memory.

Full Memory
    |
    +-- Persistent Content
    |
    +-- Short Retrieval Form
    |
    +-- Category
    |
    +-- Subcategory
    |
    +-- Entities
    |
    +-- Topics
    |
    +-- Embedding
    |
    +-- Relationships

The retrieval system searches the inexpensive representations first.

Full memory content is expanded only after relevance has been established.

Core principle

Store broadly. Retrieve narrowly. Expand progressively.
